{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17470933","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17470933"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"answeredAt":null,"options":[],"response":null,"finalizedAt":null},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"199"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17471201","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17471201"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:45:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:45:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"199"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"199","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/199"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.1,0.33,0.04,0.32]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"199"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77206"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"199","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/199"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"199"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62713"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1206"},{"type":"tags","id":"1259"},{"type":"tags","id":"1278"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6205"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7736"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42982"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44021"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77206","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77206"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 12-year-old girl presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-day history of a limp and aching sensation in her left hip. The pain occurs after playing games at school and settles with rest. She has no history of trauma and was previously well. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her BMI is 19 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. There is tenderness over her left anterior superior iliac spine. She has full and pain-free range of movement of both hips, including internal rotation. Examination of her knees and back is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reassurance that symptoms will resolve spontaneously","Hip ultrasound","Diclofenac, rest and review in one week","Full blood count and C-reactive protein","Plain X-rays of the hip"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThere are a number of causes for hip pain in children and the following should be considered:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESeptic joint\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EApophysitis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInflammatory arthritis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESlipped capital femoral epiphysis (SCFE)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELegg-Calve-Perthes disease\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features typical of traction apophysitis - activity-related hip pain that improves with rest, localised tenderness over the anterior superior iliac spine, and preserved range of movement. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe history and examination findings help exclude more serious conditions. However, more serious and sinister causes of pain need to be considered and excluded:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAtraumatic groin pain is always a\u00a0major concern and SCFE should always be considered, although this is more likely in overweight boys age 10-14\u00a0years old. It is very\u00a0unlikely when pain free hip internal rotation is preserved as this is\u00a0often the first clinical sign.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe is well, with no suggestion of infection, so a septic process is unlikely.\u00a0Septic\u00a0arthritis of the hip would be uncommon in this age group and would present with\u00a0inability to weight bear, intense pain to hip range of motion and\u00a0systemic features of infection such as fevers.\u00a0Kocher criteria can be used to distinguish septic arthritis from transient synovitis in a child with an inflammed hip. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPerthes disease more commonly presents in the younger child between 6-8 years old and presentation at this age whilst not impossible would be unusual.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiclofenac, rest and review in one week\u003C/strong\u003E is appropriate first-line management for apophysitis. Non-steroidal anti-inflammatory medications help reduce pain and inflammation, while activity modification allows healing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlain X-rays of the hip\u003C/strong\u003E are not necessary as the initial investigation given the typical presentation of apophysitis. However, if symptoms persist despite conservative management, imaging may be warranted to exclude other pathology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReassurance that symptoms will resolve spontaneously\u003C/strong\u003E without any active management is inadequate, as the patient requires symptom relief and advice about activity modification to prevent ongoing issues.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHip ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E would not be helpful in this presentation as the symptoms and signs point to an extra-articular cause. Ultrasound is more useful for detecting joint effusions or synovitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFull blood count and C-reactive protein\u003C/strong\u003E are not indicated as there are no features suggesting infection or inflammation. The patient is well, afebrile, and has preserved hip movement..\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Apophysitis is a common cause of hip pain in active adolescents and typically presents with activity-related pain that improves with rest","Pain-free internal rotation of the hip helps exclude serious conditions like slipped capital femoral epiphysis","Conservative management with NSAIDs and activity modification is appropriate first-line treatment for apophysitis"],"references":["Ref: Launay F. Sports-related overuse injuries in children. Orthop Traumatol Sure Res. 2015;101:S139-47. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25555804/","Kocher Criteria. In: MDCalc [online]. Available at: https://www.mdcalc.com/kocher-criteria-septic-arthritis"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62713"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"199"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62713","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62713"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T11:32:33+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T11:32:34+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"199"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77206"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/